## What landed in \`ferrotorch-train/src/learner.rs\`

### New \`Learner\` field + builder
- \`grad_scaler: Option<GradScaler<T>>\` — None by default; set via the new \`with_grad_scaler(scaler)\` builder.
- \`skipped_steps: usize\` — counts how many steps the scaler discarded due to inf/NaN gradients. Public accessor \`skipped_steps()\` surfaces it. Resets at the start of every \`fit\` call.

### Training-loop wiring
The \`fit\` body now branches on whether a scaler is present:

\`\`\`rust
if let Some(ref mut scaler) = self.grad_scaler {
    let scaled = scaler.scale(&loss)?;
    scaled.backward()?;
    let stepped = scaler.step(self.optimizer.as_mut())?;
    if !stepped { self.skipped_steps += 1; }
    scaler.update();
    self.optimizer.zero_grad()?;
} else {
    loss.backward()?;
    self.optimizer.step()?;
    self.optimizer.zero_grad()?;
}
\`\`\`

The standard (non-AMP) path is unchanged. \`scaler.step\` does the unscale + inf/NaN check + optimizer.step internally; \`scaler.update\` adjusts the scale factor dynamically based on whether the step was successful.

## Tests (3 new)
- \`test_learner_grad_scaler_field_starts_none\` — default constructor leaves it None
- \`test_learner_with_grad_scaler_attaches\` — builder wiring works
- \`test_learner_skipped_steps_counter_starts_zero\` — counter starts at 0

8 learner tests pass total. \`cargo test --workspace --no-fail-fast --features cuda\`: zero regressions.

## Note
The \`TrainingCheckpoint\` struct in \`ferrotorch-serialize\` doesn't currently include scaler state. For full resumability of mid-training AMP runs, the checkpoint format will need a versioned extension to add a \`grad_scaler_state: Option<GradScalerState>\` field. That's a serialize-side change with backward-compat implications — better as a separate issue.
